Example of a rank-based test

We’ll make our own samples, using a pseudorandom generator

set.seed(1414)
gp_1 <- sample.int(20, size = 15, replace = TRUE)

set.seed(1424)
gp_2 <- sample.int(30, size = 15, replace = TRUE)
hist(gp_1)

hist(gp_2)

Try a t-test:

t.test(gp_1, gp_2)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  gp_1 and gp_2
## t = -1.3241, df = 23.545, p-value = 0.1982
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -9.558315  2.091648
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  11.40000  15.13333

What is the meaning of the p-value? If these samples were drawn from populations with the same mean, the probability of taking two random samples with means at least as different as the sample means we found by random chance (taking into account spread, n) is 19.8%.

Retain (fail to reject) the null hypothesis. >> There is no significant difference in means between group 1 and group 2.

Warning: people get wirdly upset if you say “accept” the null.

Now let’s compare this outcome to a rank-based test.

Mann Whitney U unpaired rank-based test

mwu <- wilcox.test(gp_1, gp_2)
## Warning in wilcox.test.default(gp_1, gp_2): cannot compute exact p-value with
## ties
mwu
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  gp_1 and gp_2
## W = 86, p-value = 0.28
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

Meaning of p-value of 0.28: If these samples were drawn from populations with the same ranks (medians), the probability of finding two samples with ranks at least as different as those in our samples is 0.28.

There is no significant difference in ranks (often you’ll see medians) between group 1 and group 2 (statistical summary).

Median scores for group 1 (M = 14) and group 2 (M = 12) did not differ significantly (Mann Whitney U test: U(df) = 86, p = 0.28)

To look at documentation: type in ?wilcox.test then you can recall values with mwu$p.value, etc.

Linear regression

Simple linear regression (single dependent variable, a single independent variable)

Find a linear regression model using ordinary least squares describing the relationship between flipper length and body mass for these penguins.

3 pieces:

  • What type of model?
  • What is the relationship to model (DV - IV(s))?
  • Where is the data that’s sued to create this model?
penguin_lm <- lm(body_mass_g ~ flipper_length_mm, data = penguins)

y = mx + b y is body mass x is flipper length body mass = 49.7(flipper length) - 5780.83 what is the coefficient for flipper length? The slope! On average, I expect for every one mm increase in flipper length, I expect a 49.7 gram increase in body mass! units = g/mm

-5780.08 units would be grams Interpretation: this intercept is not meaningful. Would have to extend flipper length to 0.

broom package returns model outputs as tidy data frames

penguin_lm_tidy <- broom::tidy(penguin_lm)

broom::glance(penguin_lm) #gives model-wide uncertainties and whatnot in a nice data frame - more on Wednesday
## # A tibble: 1 × 12
##   r.squared adj.r.squared sigma statistic   p.value    df logLik   AIC   BIC
##       <dbl>         <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     0.759         0.758  394.     1071. 4.37e-107     1 -2528. 5063. 5074.
## # … with 3 more variables: deviance <dbl>, df.residual <int>, nobs <int>

How can I actually include my model equation in a report?

extract_eq(model = penguin_lm, use_coefs = TRUE)

\[ \operatorname{\widehat{body\_mass\_g}} = -5780.83 + 49.69(\operatorname{flipper\_length\_mm}) \]

plot(penguin_lm)
